According to TypeSpec official documentation on Directives (https://typespec.io/docs/language-basics/directives/), directives (including `#suppress`) are predefined annotations that attach to syntax nodes (â€śattach to the syntax nodesâ€ť), meaning a `#suppress` only applies to the specific type/model/property/operation node it is written on (i.e., immediately above that node), rather than acting as a file-level setting. Therefore, when suppressing a warning, `#suppress` should be placed directly above the node that produces the warning, not at the file header. This node-scoped placement also makes it clear and auditable exactly which code triggered the warning, so reviewers can unambiguously locate the warning source and understand what is being suppressed.
